// Roman gods × 12 — the Dii Consentes, the twelve canonical state-deities of
// the Roman religion as named by Ennius (c. 200 BCE), formalized by Livy
// (22.10, 217 BCE *lectisternium* of the twelve gods), and listed by
// Cicero (*De Natura Deorum*) and Varro (*Antiquitates Rerum Divinarum*).
// SEO funnel at /gab44/roman-gods (index) + /gab44/roman-gods/{slug}.
//
// THIRTEENTH pantheon on gab44. Companion to /gab44/olympians (the Greek
// twelve) but structurally distinct: Greek religion was *personality-and-
// myth* centered; Roman religion was *state, household, contract, and
// numen* centered. The Greek question was "what story does this god live
// in?"; the Roman question was "what *jurisdiction* does this god govern
// and what is the *correct ritual formula* (the *carmen*) to address them
// by?" Almost all popular knowledge of "Roman" gods is actually Greek
// mythology with Roman names attached — the result of the *interpretatio
// graeca* that began in the 3rd c. BCE when Rome conquered Magna Graecia
// and imported the Greek myth-corpus wholesale. This module separates the
// distinctly-Roman elements (state-cult, household-cult, ritual-formula,
// uniquely-Roman deities like Janus and Quirinus and Bellona that have no
// Greek counterpart, the Vestal-Virgin institution, the Lares-and-Penates
// household-shrine) from the Greek-imports.
//
// Three families × 4 deities, drawn from the Dii Consentes (the twelve
// state-gods whose gilded statues stood in the Forum at the Porticus Deorum
// Consentium, the colonnade rebuilt by the prefect Vettius Praetextatus in
// 367 CE as one of the last public acts of Roman state-paganism before
// Theodosius's 391 CE closure):
//
//   1. Capitoline Triad & Sovereign Brothers (Jupiter, Juno, Minerva,
//      Neptune) — the Capitoline-Hill state-trinity (Jupiter Optimus
//      Maximus, Juno Regina, Minerva Medica, sharing the great temple
//      whose foundations are still visible under the Palazzo dei
//      Conservatori) plus Neptune (Jupiter's brother, sovereign of the
//      sea and of horses and of freshwater springs).
//
//   2. State-Cult: War, Hearth, Grain, Forge (Mars, Vesta, Ceres, Vulcan)
//      — the four pillars of the Roman state-religion: Mars the founder-
//      father of Rome (Mars and Rhea Silvia begat Romulus and Remus, so
//      every Roman was *Marte genitus*); Vesta the perpetual-flame whose
//      Vestal Virgins kept the fire of the state burning continuously
//      from c. 700 BCE to 394 CE; Ceres the grain-mother whose plebeian
//      cult on the Aventine was the political-counterweight to the
//      patrician Capitoline cult; Vulcan the forge-god whose Vulcanalia
//      festival on August 23 marked the most fire-dangerous moment of
//      the Roman year.
//
//   3. Personal Patrons: Light, Hunt, Love, Travel (Apollo, Diana, Venus,
//      Mercury) — the four gods Romans addressed *individually* rather
//      than *as a citizen*: Apollo the imported-Greek light-prophecy-
//      music god whom Augustus made his personal patron; Diana the
//      Aventine-cult hunt-and-moon-virgin who was the goddess of slaves
//      and runaways and the *jus asyli*; Venus the genetrix of the
//      Julian gens (and through Caesar of all subsequent emperors);
//      Mercury the messenger and *especially* the patron of merchants
//      and the trade-routes.
//
// Source-honest: every page cites the actual Latin-source corpus —
// Virgil's *Aeneid* (29-19 BCE, the foundational poem of Roman
// religious-political identity), Ovid's *Metamorphoses* (8 CE) and
// *Fasti* (8 CE, the only surviving day-by-day commentary on the
// Roman ritual calendar), Livy's *Ab Urbe Condita* (27 BCE-9 CE,
// books 1-10 the canonical history of the early Republic and its
// religious institutions), Cicero's *De Natura Deorum* (45 BCE, the
// philosophical-skeptical interrogation of Roman theology), Varro's
// surviving fragments of *Antiquitates Rerum Divinarum* (47 BCE,
// the lost ethnographic-encyclopedic treatment of Roman religion
// reconstructed from Augustine's *De Civitate Dei*), Plutarch's *Roman
// Questions* (c. 100 CE, the 113-question Greek-perspective inquiry
// into Roman ritual oddities), Macrobius's *Saturnalia* (c. 430 CE,
// the last great pagan symposium), Pliny the Elder, Suetonius —
// plus modern scholarship: Jörg Rüpke (*Religion of the Romans*),
// Mary Beard / John North / Simon Price (*Religions of Rome*),
// Robert Turcan, John Scheid (*An Introduction to Roman Religion*),
// H. H. Scullard (*Festivals and Ceremonies of the Roman Republic*).
//
// Shadow-honest: each page names (a) the *interpretatio graeca* erasure
// — most popular "Roman mythology" is Greek myth with Roman name-stickers
// applied, and the distinctly-Roman elements (the carmen-formula, the
// auspicia, the divus-cult, the Lares-and-Penates, the indigitamenta list
// of minor-deities-for-each-tiny-act) have been culturally lost; (b)
// the 380 CE *Edict of Thessalonica* under Theodosius I that made
// Nicene Christianity the sole official religion, the 391 CE closure
// of pagan temples, the 394 CE Battle of the Frigidus where the last
// army marching under Roman religious banners (Eugenius's forces with
// Flavianus and Symmachus among the senators carrying Hercules-Victor
// imagery) was defeated by Theodosius — the formal end of the Roman
// state cult; (c) the 1922-1945 *Roma Eterna* fascist appropriation
// under Mussolini, including the explicit Marte-Genitor-of-the-Italian-
// people propaganda, the SPQR insignia on Fascist Party buildings, the
// 1937 Mostra Augustea della Romanità, and the 1938 Racial Laws framed
// as restoration of Roman state-religion; (d) the contemporary far-
// right *Romanitas* appropriation (Bannon, Vance, Carlson invoking
// "Western civilization", classical-statue debates, "based-Roman"
// online meme aesthetic); (e) the 21st-c. *Cultus Deorum Romanorum*
// neo-pagan revival movement (Nova Roma, the Religio Romana Project)
// which has done legitimate scholarly recovery-work alongside the
// political-appropriation noise; (f) the Latin-calendar legacy
// embedded in every Western language: January = Janus (Roman threshold-
// god with no Greek counterpart), March = Mars, May = Maia (Mercury's
// mother), June = Juno, Saturday = Saturn-day, plus the Romance-
// language days (mardi=Mars, mercredi=Mercury, jeudi=Jupiter, vendredi=
// Venus); and (g) the *no-myths* aspect of original Roman religion —
// before the 3rd-c.-BCE Greek imports, Roman deities had *no narrative
// stories at all*, only *jurisdictions* and *carmina*, and the recovery
// of that pre-Greek Roman religious-imagination is one of the major
// ongoing tasks of contemporary classical scholarship.

